and elevation of the scapula"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eextension, adduction and internal rotation of the shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary actions of the latissimus dorsi muscle (image). It is a powerful extensor, adductor and internal rotator of the glenohumeral joint, pulling the arm downward and backward.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexion and lateral flexion of the trunk\u003C/strong\u003E - While latissimus dorsi can assist in these movements when acting bilaterally or unilaterally, these are not its primary actions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbduction and internal rotation of the shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E - While latissimus dorsi does internally rotate the shoulder, it performs adduction, not abduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexion and external rotation of the shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E - These movements are antagonistic to the true actions of latissimus dorsi\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtraction and elevation of the scapula\u003C/strong\u003E - These are movements of the scapula, which is not directly acted upon by latissimus dorsi\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe latissimus dorsi muscle originates from the spinous processes of T7-L5 vertebrae, thoracolumbar fascia, iliac crest, and inferior ribs, and inserts into the floor of the intertubercular groove of the humerus. It is innervated by the thoracodorsal nerve (C6-C8).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The latissimus dorsi muscle originates from the spinous processes of T7-L5 vertebrae, thoracolumbar fascia, iliac crest, and inferior ribs.","The latissimus dorsi muscle inserts into the intertubercular groove of the humerus.","The primary actions of latissimus dorsi are extension, adduction, and internal rotation of the shoulder joint."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cLatissimus dorsi muscle\u201d by Anatomography\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 2.1 jp Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.1/jp/deed.en). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Latissimus_dorsi_muscle_back.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63875"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18519"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21407"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21407"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Kiw6NZp8F5xJZec1AY8UJu5VX9Qu3O.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Kiw6NZp8F5xJZec1AY8UJu5VX9Qu3O.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":640}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63875"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T11:40:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T11:41:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11248"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78534"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical studen